<Rating>5</Rating>< text>
This is a well run marina. The docks run E-W so the boats are subjected to wind from the beam most of the time making getting into and out of slips a little more fun, but not a big deal. Decent bathrooms and laundry facilities that are kept clean. Management is friendly and helpful.<//text>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
We have been docking our power boat at the SIM for about two plus years. Joe and his team have always been customer oriented. They are all very helpful and available. The marina and restrooms are always clean and safe. They are very accommodating when there are special needs  and have kept us updated on weather conditions when necessary. I highly recommend this marina. John A.<//Review>

<review>I've been here twice now and both visit's were absolutely amazing. First time I had my lamb meat (Mmmm so tender) with their Tom Yum broth and the second visit I went with the Spicy Pork Bone broth. I have to say both soup bases were delicious and well worth the money (and the long wait on the first visit). Speaking on wait time, this place can get a bit crowded on the weekends, so I suggest coming earlier to put your name down. (There's plenty of things to walk around to and explore in this plaza!)

On to their sauce bar. They have different combinations posted up with a very good selection of sauces to choose from. I like the clean set up of this sauce bar, which i'm definitely comparing to other hot pot locations i've been too.

This place has Sapporo on draft and is only $2.50 a glass! Definitely a must to have a glass of beer to go along with such a mouth watering meal.</review>< pics>

<Gmap_id>0x80c32a618ac28999:0x98a8b1774bdafcc8< /Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
< Time>
1448481875294< /Time>
<Pics>None< /Pics><Text>Shabu shabu customization at its best!

Ichi ichi is for those meals with your polar opposite, because no matter what, both of you can find something you like here. Customers have the ability to choose their own broth flavor, meat and sauces.

1. Choose your broth from around 25 flavors (spicy pork bone, spicy sichuan, tom yum, milky, Japanese curry, to miso and corn cream, to name a few...) for about $10-$15 a pot.
2. Pick your meat: pork, lamb, chicken breast, beef and premium angus beef (for $3 extra). Regular servings are about 10 slices, and you can upgrade to large for $3 more.
3. Concoct your perfect dipping sauce at Sauce Blvd., which offers eggs, sesame, daikon, bbq sauce, spicy oil, white/red vinegar, 2 types of garlic* (dried and freshly diced!), etc...
Note: If you want to share a pot, there's a $2 sauce charge.

We had the spicy pork bone and the miso and corn, and both were aromatically addicting. Make your money go the distance by taking leftovers home, adding some veggies+tofu+noodles, and second mealing it!

*garlic makes the world go 'round<//Text>< response>

Mandi Tom</Name>
<time>1397601787560</time><Rate>4<//Rate><Review>Located on the corner of Colima and Fullerton at the Yes plaza.

Plenty of bar seating, some tables.... relatively OK with seating arrangements. If you come with a big group - be warned, there are only two large tables. Also, if you get a booth table, you share the same pot (split in the middle) with your companion.

All three of us got the same thing - Beef (one small (8 slices of beef)/two medium orders (12 slices)) with the Spicy Pork Bone Broth in medium spiciness. Definitely an awesome broth! Thank you fellow yelpers, definitely didn't steer me in the wrong direction. My complaint - I had way less spice in my soup and had to add extra spicy oil. Should have asked for the spice dropper instead of the oil. Oh well.

They serve draft beer - Sapporo and sake. $11.50/pitcher; $3.50 glass - $2.50 during happy hour. They have lunch specials and happy hour appetizers and drinks.

LOVED, loved the DIY sauce bar. It had virtually every sauce you may want for your shabu-shabu and you can create your concoction to your taste buds. I ended up with almost a bowl of sauce with a little of everything.

However, what I started concocting:
Sauce 1 - Peanut sauce, fresh chopped garlic, and daikon.
Sauce 2 - Ponzo, Satay, Fresh chopped garlic and daikon
Sauce 3 - Satay, fresh chopped garlic and daikon with hot chili oil
Sauce 4 - Satay, extra chili oil, garlic, and cilantro.

After a while, this just became one jumble of sauces. :) Oh allegedly one egg per person, but how would they know if you took more than one? The eggs were placed at the sauce station. I guess they would know when they're picking up the shells.

Btw - I need additional types of veggies on my platter. The veggie platter is standard - one leaf of bok choy (yup ONE leaf), a few chopped up leaves of nappa, 1/2 a shitake mushroom, a slice of pumpkin, some enoki, 2 tabs of tofu, and some udon. I guess I wanted more bok choy, which I could have ordered. And they were out of the fish balls with fish roe inside. I cry! :(

I'd come back. But will try to have another type of soup.< /Review><Pics>None</Pics><response>None</response><GmapID>0x80c32a618ac28999:0x98a8b1774bdafcc8< /GmapID></record>

<UserId.>108975433585922436755</UserId.><name>Sherlyn Menezes<//name><Time>1615611729818</Time><Rating>3</Rating><Review>NOTE: Sasaki reopened their outdoor dining in Feb 2021. That's when I visited them.

Covid protocol: staff wear masks and gloves. All guests are required to wear masks. They provide hand sanitizers.

Food: Omakese is $80 per person that contains Amuse(we got a bite size piece of pumpkin), Chef's choice nine pieces of Nigiri with one Temaki(hand rolled sushi cone) and Tamago(Japanese omelette).
We ordered an additional Toro nigiri (fatty tuna) that cost $14 per piece.
All fish was fresh and melted in the mouth.

Ambience: there isn't any to be honest. You are out on the street just watching the vehicles go by. Hope the indoor dining opens soon.

Service: the servers were polite and explained what each dish was when they served it.<//Review><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPZBG_gCfueUTHhWhpT85_nU91qBg40_l07A1Jd=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOkLya1BY1sMi4q-iRC8R7SxX5SjjxJJLYsQqOv=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNSVL4kn5oD2muTWmy0Rs35HTV3c0d3qoESHGAC=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMhhBY5aMPTUG8_B7k_AO6pzYXHK481vuVxi8Tk=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNpuFEyP0jqXSUpgae7k_3JnQ9OaHjzqGyUCvR7=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMPLX1tJnOS83n4g9XSLXiz_2biioUyPM2hLO9-=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pictures>< response>

<Date>1619739654231</Date><rate>5<//rate><Review>It has been a while visiting Sasaki due to the virus.
Well balanced shari and neta overall! I think that Sasakisan's shari to tane ratio is off a little bit. He doesn't always use enough shari when forming the nigiri, and on some pieces it felt as if the balance of the nigiri suffered because of it but still normally B+ ~ A+ range.
Sasaki is the only sushiya that I'm aware of in the Bay Area that prepares two batches of rice, each seasoned differently, to best complement whatever tane is being served (Sushi Sho style). This is no small task and it indicates the level of care that the chefs are willing to put in to deliver a great dining experience.
Always one of my favorite omakase lists.< /Review><pictures>None<//pictures>< Resp>

<Review>The fishes were excellent, but I found the rice to be too sour, and it overpowered the fish. There were some pieces, such as Toro, Uni, and Aji that stood up to the rice, but for some other pieces, all you can taste is the vinegar. Overall, a decent experience, but for the price I would not go back. (Not an expert here so take my review with a grain of salt.)</Review></record>
</dataset><record>
< text>
Unassuming exterior leads into a beautifully spartan sushi counter. Welcome was warm and friendly. Lovely amuse and starter dishes. The progression of nigiri is somewhat unusual compared to many other omakase I've been to. Here, rather than having a build up of white fish leading up to the fatty fishes, chef groups the nigiri into three movements, each with their ebs and flows. The quality of the fish is outstanding, but the artistry comes from the rice. Chef uses differently seasoned rice for each movement, to match the type and cure of the fish.
Amazing sushi.</text>

106485379244315907848</UserId.>
<rating>2< /rating>< username>
Rodrigo Lagos<//username>
< Resp>
None</Resp>
< Text>
My wife and I have dined at most of the SF Omakase restaurants.
In SF this is a 2 star Omakase - in other places, maybe a 4 star.
The quality of each course was up and down throughout the meal. The Toro was highlight, along with the Uni. Many others were lacking in flavor and range. I wish they had kept to a smaller menu and took the quality higher and more creative execution. The Tamago was a huge disappointment, overly sweet and the texture ranged gritty to dry overdone, this to me was far off the mark of a high end restaurant.
The other lacking factor was the ambiance of the chef and staff. Everyone was courteous and welcoming, but I saw little delight in the chef's work. He kept to himself and shared next to nothing about what we were eating - it's great when you have a chef that tells a bit of the story behind the food, it adds another layer to the experience.

For $180 a head there needs to be a pretty good delivery on all courses and experience.
You can take the same money to 2 or 3 other places in the city and walk away with more value.</Text>
</record>
</dataset><record>

105603284385958429156<//userid>
< GmapID>
0x808f7e375f5f8951:0xe78382e7c8fd964e< /GmapID>
< time>
1491411893928< /time>
< Text>
The door is quite inconspicuous, there's no obvious sign, but it is that large door on the corner of where google maps takes you.

Food - Amazing! Loved almost everything. Although it is pricy at $180/person, the amount of food you get...oh my...by the end of the meal I was way too stuffed. I kind of wish they had a $120 version where I wouldn't leave feeling as if I were about to burst.

The menu starts with 5 extremely special pieces. Every piece is carefully crafted close to perfection. The taste, the texture, and the amount of time they put into marinating some of these pieces. Everything they serve is seasonal depending on what fresh ingredients they can get. Then it goes into 13 nigiris and then the soup and dessert.

The interior is also beautiful! Unlike many sushi restaurants,  they have high ceilings and a very spacious bar seating. They don't have any tables, thus they only serve their omakase menu.

I would highly recommend this restaurant for a special night where you want to splurge for high quality sushi. Come with an appetite!< /Text>

< text>
You'd miss this place if you were headed there... At least pre Covid... Great service, quality food and knowledgeable team. Brown rice is used for the nigiri, which is interesting. All sushi is seasoned by the chef so you won't find soy sauce or wasabi on the table. That's a good thing!< /text>

This was our second time dining here, waiting a year in between, and is a bit of a hidden gem in the Mission. It's more of a traditional place and the chef is definitely a master of his craft. There are a lot more omakase places in the city now and this one is up there in price. But it's well executed, you are definitely full at the end and would be a nice place to take a date or for a quiet celebratory dinner.<//Text>

Justin was awesome! He then tried to give me a total due of over $300, citing that I would receive two tempered glass lifetime warranty glass screen covers included. I felt like a kindergarten teacher trying to get information out of a reluctant five year old, using pointed questions, to finally get him to admit that they were $60 each!! He then claimed I was getting a deal at $40 each. When I declined them, yet again, my total dropped by over $120. Hmmmm, must be the new math. He added Total Protection to two phones, $26 a month extra, and did not tell me he was doing this, or ask me if I wanted it. I'm normally very pleased w/verizon. Always had good experiences, but this time I spoke to Ross and whoever the manager was (I forgot his name) at the time and I wanted to get a phone upgrade for my husbands birthday. they said that they are having a buy one get one free. Well, to our surprise, we were charged for both phones. I called verizon customer service and they were great and can only do what they can do and they took some charges off of our bill but I'm still seriously hurt by those two individuals not honoring the buy one get one free. I didn't have nothing in writing from them stating that it was a bogo. I went in there twice that day and spoke to them about the offer but because it's an AUTHORIZED RETAILER....things are done a little bit differently so my experience is from now on, if you want to take advantage of their offers please have someone give it to you in writing and have them sign it so if you have to call verizon customer service you will have proof. When verizon customer service called the AUTHORIZED RETAILER, they had no knowledge. From my understanding the offer was only good until the 21st. We went in on the 26th. Had they told us I would have done things a little bit differently. So please be careful with these AUTHORIZED RETAILERS. I would suggest going to the actual verizon store. I won't be going back to that one any time soon. I'm pretty disappointed. There was other stuff regarding the tablets and hums but I was not too worried about that mainly the buy one get one free phones....Please be careful in the future. Again, get everything in writing INCLUDING THE PRICE!!! ESPECIALLY THE PRICE!!!. Make sure you know what the cost is going to be before you walk out the store and what your monthly bill will be. Get clarity, We have never had a problem with Verizon but I'm just going to do things differently from now on.< /Text>

<Date>1619328726547< /Date><name>J Co.</name>< text>
I want to start by saying I loved the view. From the moment you walk in, you imagine you will have a great experience. We had a reservation, so when we walked to the main lobby we were told to wait a couple of minutes. After a few minutes a waiter came around and asked us to follow her. She asked if we were celebrating any special occasion, I told her "yes, anniversary", and she congratulated us. We followed her through the building to the main yard, and went all the way to the lower courtyard. My first impression was that the building was beautiful, the courtyard was even more pretty with all the pretty Valley lights and nice setting. However, the lower courtyard had plastic tables that really took away from the fancy dinner I expected. Regardless, we sat by one of the middle tables for 4, even though we were just 2, with a half view of the Valley and a very empty looking plastic table. We ordered 2 New York Steaks and a few drinks. After one hour of waiting, the nice waiter came around with our orders. We asked for well done steaks and got medium rare. My husband's steak was semi-cold. The mashed potatoes got my 5 stars, it was one of the best mashed potatoes I have ever had at a restaurant. The drinks were nice too, I had a mimosa and a margarita. Both were good, just very low on alcohol, but I was glad about that. For the very expensive dinner I was honestly expecting a grand occasion, but neither the food nor the location was up to my dreamed anniversary dinner.
Overall it was a nice experience, I don't think I will be coming back anytime soon. Next time, if I ever come back, I will try the main building and hopefully get my well done steaks.</text>

Food was good -well some of it, but I didn't think is was for the prices. However, I had agreed to go there to pick up food for Valentine's day as my husband loves prime rib. When ordering he requested to swap out his sides for a baked potato, so I asked the same for french fries. We drove from Hollywood to collect our special dinner however I realised I too had a baked potato. I didn't think much of it at first. I'm a pescatarian so I had ordered the salmon, very small compared to my husband's steak. Then I realised the potatos were covered in thick chunks of bacon, trying not to make a big deal of it as I didn't want to ruin my husband meal I removed the bacon. Unfortunately after undressing my potato I could see it had dark almost black marks through out the vegetable. Really very underwhelmed at the experience but at least my husband enjoyed his steak.<//text>

<user_name>John Kahwaty< /user_name>< review>
Odyssey is a fun restaurant with a great view.  The actual restaurant part of the property lines the front window over looking the valley.  It is very similar to the pre-renovated castaway's in Burbank if you've ever been there.  We had the salmon, filet mignon, and the prime rib.  The salmon was excellent, but both the filet and prime rib were overcooked and under seasoned.  They give lots of bread while you wait which is nice but the butter is unsalted so grab that salt shaker.  All of their potatoe sides were very good.  Their other sides weren't as good.  They have a non-alcoholic drink with lemonade and strawberry that was awesome.  Overall it was a little pricey for the quality of food and the inside is looking a little older, but it is in a great location with a pretty decent array of items on the menu.  I would go again.<//review>

< text>
We attended a wedding reception here on a Saturday recently. We were in a banquet room and had access to the buffet brunch in the main seating area. It grieves me to say that the food was less than mediocre and in some cases not edible. As we were guests at the wedding reception we did not complain about the food but we were sorely disappointed. Also halfway into our event another event began celebrating next to us and the walls are so thin that the mariachi band and the noise overshadowed and overpowered our entire afternoon. Nobody could hear our music or the people on the microphone and it was extremely frustrating. Obviously we enjoyed ourselves because we were with our friends celebrating loved ones nuptials but the restaurant left a lot to be desired. I can say however that the service was excellent. Our waiter was extremely attentive and quick with our request for drinks and cleaned up immediately after and was extremely charming. I probably would not go back to this restaurant in the future.<//text>

Sunday brunch is $49, but a wide variety of choices and everything you can imagine from beef, sea food, fruits, salads, omelet bar, deserts, beverages.  Staff is OK.  Ambience is very nice. < Review>
I honestly tried this place a couple of times before I did this review.  This place has been slowly declining year by year and it is a true disappointment. Beautiful views but awful food. So this review is regarding my recent visit on Wednesday, December 12 for the buffet lunch. Now, this brunch was $32 all you can eat and $4.50 for a soda. The first problem was the food was overcooked and dry, especially the meats. Flavor was weak and the taste was bland. The next issue was it was all you can eat, but they did not refill the food. I was basically eating leftovers! What was ridiculous was the crabs, there were only small scraps when I got there, so I decided to ask the server if there will be more crabs. The gentleman took the tray and said he will bring some more out, half an hour later, NOTHING! As for the clam chowder, the pot was completely sizzling with the dry remains in it. Now the desert I was expecting to be at least decent, but it was not! Again nothing was left and nor did they think they should put more out. Now for the chocolate roll log cake, there were little flies all over it. YUCK! I was there to celebrate an achievement but unfortunately, we picked the wrong place to celebrate. My family was going to do the Christmas brunch here, but due to the last visit, my husband changed the venue. True waste of money.<//Review>

We were here for a wedding Saturday June 15th.  Nice setting for the ceremony and the halls are right next to that area, so it's a convenient setting.  The ballroom with the existing shear fabric and lights are  very decorative and a nice touch to any event. < review>
My wife and I celebrated our first wedding anniversary at the Odessy Thursday night and are so happy we did.
Walking in was breathtaking....the view of the city lights set the stage. We were greeted kindly by the hostess and seated immediately, which was great because the place was packed with people. Our server Donnie was incredible. He was professional and personnel and made us feel special. He made many recommendations which we went with. We started with mojitos which were great but dove into a sampler plate with prime rib tacos and calamari that was so tasty. Donnie recommended the salmon for my wife and a rib eye for myself as I was hungry. The wines he paired were perfect and the entrees were some of the best we have ever had.
Five stars to the Odessy......we will see you for the buffet on Sunday. It's our new spot< /review>

<date>1559228188368<//date><rating>4</rating>< review>
This a must visit at some point if you live in the valley area. The views are absolutely gorgeous. Personally I prefer the bar area over the sit down restaurant or the patio. It is a great place to head to right before sunset so you get the sunset and the gorgeous twinkle of the valley. On a clear day you can see ridiculously far. I have also attended a number of events here and the food/organization of the event was great. It is not he newest/more over the top glamorous venue but it is solid, established and there won't be surprises here. I have been here in Jean and in formal attire and the venue has the ability to morph depending on the occasion.< /review>

< text>
I was brought to Odyssey for a surprise birthday brunch. There was a reservation for 2, but upon arrival, the greeter couldn't find it. However, the greeter made things work and we were seated within 10 minutes.

I took a gander around the buffet before I piled up. There were a lot of options ranging from sushi to fresh seafood (clams, crab legs, and shrimp) to meat to breakfast items. Basically, there's something for everyone. My favorites included the breakfast potatoes and the clams. There was even a custom-made omelet bar!

After all that eating, how could I not make more room for dessert?! Lots of varieties of desserts, but my favorite was the make your own chocolate covered strawberries/pineapples/etc station.

There's a staff member that takes complimentary photos, prints on the spot, and the option to buy the bigger size.

Overall, I had a great birthday brunch experience here and I hope I can come back at night time to take in the beautiful skyline view.< /text>

<Name>Mindy D.</Name><date>1539444691925<//date><Rating>4</Rating>< Text>
My husband and I had our first date here 33 years ago. Being back in town on a visit,  we thought we would relive the moment. Much of it was like we remembered. I was disappointed however to learn that they no longer offer their salad bar (only the Sunday brunch hours).  And the coconut fried shrimp I used to get was no longer on the menu,  but they serve a grilled polynesian shrimp that was equally as good. They are celebrating their 60th anniversary with a special throw back menu for the month of October (and maybe November).  The food was great and our server was very sweet. We were glad they still have the fire pits on the back patio where we always enjoyed an after dinner drink and watched the city lights. We were also treated to a spectacular lighting show!  I chose to give a 4 star instead of 5 because of the lack of the salad bar,  especially on a Friday night.</Text>

<user>112043637222205858373<//user><rating>5<//rating><Gmap_id>0x80c29011ba9d643d:0xa5ea6e4db9be3f1e</Gmap_id><user_name>Alex Martinez<//user_name><pictures>None</pictures><Review>I've been a fan of the Odyssey's Sunday Brunch for years. There's no better way to prime a lazy Sunday morning than eating with friends, family or parents. The serving staff is always courteous and attentive, the food is varied and savory, and the view is unparalleled. It's well worth the drive out.

When looking at venues for a small (<100 guests) wedding, I was constantly stumped by overblown prices at other locales. The Odyssey's special events planners presented to me a package that was quite simply unmatchable. They included a buffet-style dinner with remarkable food and a dessert cart with coffee and pastries towards the evening's end, at a fraction of the cost that other venues had presented to me. My wife and I sprang for an open bar and a chocolate fountain for a little more. Even then, the price was spectacular. The Odyssey's staff was very easy to work with, and the day of the event they provided our guests with matchless service. The food was so well received that my guests still -- 3 years after the event-- rave about their meal and drinks that night.

Consider the Odyssey for your next big event. You won't be disappointed!<//Review>< response>

This used to be a fine restaurant. Last night I took my wife, and we found the experience to be very mediocre. We had the fillet mignon,  which I don't mind paying a high price for if it's really great. It was definitely not worth the $37 per plate. It was good, but not memorable. Those 2 tables stayed dirty with dishes and champagne bottles on them, and the broken glass stayed on the ground for the rest of the night. While walking around the area, we had to kick the glass under the table to keep people from stepping on it.
While waiting for service several people got up for smoke breaks. As we walked around we noticed Gatorade bottles, glasses, cups, rags, napkins, on the walkways and in the bushes.
After STILL not receiving service our birthday girl got up TWICE to go find a waitress. When we finally ordered, the waitress took our orders on a piece of folded up, used, printer paper. Not even proper tickets.
3 people ordered salads, nothing more. Those salads came out LONG before anyone else's food, so they just sat there waiting for everyone else to get their food. Once everyone finally got their food I was almost finished with my plate when one person at the end of the table finally got his plate that had been forgotten.
After dinner, several us had to go to the front desk 2 and 3 times to try and get a server to bring our check. We asked for our check while the sun was still up, we didn't leave until well after the sun was down.
If you're looking for a clean atmosphere, with reliable service, and good food for the price. Go to Denny's. I'm not kidding. I'd have rather.</Text>< pictures>

<Review>A very good restaurant with amazing views of the entire SFV. I've only been there for the sunday brunch, which I really like and have been to several times. But beware of going on a holiday or special occasion day like mother's day, they raise the prices for those special days.  There isn't anything extra done, well maybe a few flowers, and you don't get anything extra; you just get to pay more.  I used to go regularly until I happened to go on one of those special days and had no idea until they brought the check. At that time they didn't advertise or give notice to the price increase, they may have changed that since.  If prices are an issue, as it was for this memeber of a family of 5, make sure to ask ahead of time.<//Review></record></dataset><record>

0x80c29011ba9d643d:0xa5ea6e4db9be3f1e</Gmap_id>
<Rate>3</Rate><text>I wanted to take my girlfriend somewhere very special and nice for her birthday. It was easy to to reserve a table for two that day right over the phone. A really nice lady booked my reservation and answered the questions I had. Parking was easy, we were seated rather quickly, and the staff was very nice. The restaurant has a pretty nice view of the valley. When we got there the restaurant had a many open tables but the bar was very busy. It wasn't so bad on a Thursday night.
Our waiter attended us quickly with our menus and asked for drinks. Minutes later he brought our appetizer. When it came to our entrees, we ordered, but did not receive anything until many minutes later. We had finished our appetizers, drank almost all our drinks, and had finish taking pictures of the occasion. We were starting to get very impatient and wondering if they were even working on our food. 45 minutes later we finally received our food, and I had in mind that they had done somthing to perfect the food because of the time it took, but it was sad say the food was average-at-best. The taste was nothing but ordinary, and to be honest the lobster was a little overcooked and chewy.
So the main dishes weren't all that fantastic, but later came the free birthday dessert which was the comeback of the night. I've got to say that the desserts at The Odyssey do not disappoint. Her birthday brownie with ice cream on top and powdered sugar was one of the best we've ever had! And I've got to say the creme brulee wasn't so bad either.
Overall the restaurant is pretty good but if you're looking for something jaw dropping, mouth-watering, and price worthy, I suggest you keep looking. As for drinks you're very limited to just alcoholic drinks and/or water. My girlfriend and I decided it was sadly a once-in-a-lifetime visit and we don't believe we will be going back anytime soon.</text><resp>None< /resp>< Pictures>

< review>
I am wishing I could rate Odyssey as 5-star. How sad that they took an excellent view and classic wood-paneled restaurant and added poorly cooked food that is geared for catering large events. Look, rubbery shrimp, raw filets, and boring boiled red potatoes do not have a place in this restaurant. Contemporize the menu and cook food correctly. How about adding some salt, which was sorely missing? Again, okay for a wedding reception; not acceptable for a classy, romantic restaurant.

One reviewer commented about the state of repairs. We walked past a chair with the back so loose that it is an injury in the making. Staff need to report broken chairs and management needs to fit them.  This was the only repair issue we saw.

Service... hoo hum, but at least replaced the over-cooked shrimp with some that were edible.

Other than that, a great view. 5-star view and setting with 2-star food. There is potential for great restaurant, if the owners realize that their restaurant guests are at least as important as the big catering events that are hosted in other rooms.< /review>

<rating>5</rating><Text>The Odyssey is a hilltop restaurant overlooking the San Fernando Valley in Los Angeles County, California. It has wonderful food, but more importantly, the ambiance makes it special. At night you can see the entire valley laid out before you like a pile of jewels. There is a firepit out on the patio where you can eat al fresco if you want. The service is prompt, the wait staff is friendly and helpful. I went there on a first date with my future husband, and it was the most romantic, wonderful time. We closed the place down, staying till almost 2am. We had bacon wrapped filet minon with steamed vegetables, and tiramisu for dessert. It's a dinner I will never forget, because of the romance, the atmosphere, and the beautiful view of the Valley below us on a clear cool night.</Text>< Pictures>

< user_id>
100206180131731784292<//user_id>
<date>1429114422496<//date>< resp>
None< /resp>
< text>
This isn't really a place you come for food but you come for the view.

We went for date night and it was very romantic with the view outside.  The food was just OK.

The Buffalo Shrimp appetizer was very good.  I got prime rib, medium rare, and my boyfriend got the cowboy ribeye. My prime rib came medium well to well done and I think had it not been for that it would have been pretty good. But, for me, it was dry.  The augratin potatoes were delicious though and I love that they have their own farm on prem.

In another review I saw someone complain that you couldn't taste the food because it was all too salty.  I get that review but for me the salt was great.  I liked not having to add any additional and I didn't feel it was too overwhelming.

I think we would for sure go back again, as the food wasn't bad just wasn't amazing, for the view.  On a nice warm summer night it would be great to sit out on the patio.</text>

3</Rate>
< Review>
A little run down?
That's what I heard from someone else too.
We went for a company party.
Have not been there in 8 years.
We (my wife and I) were not impressed.
We went 2 hours early and sat in the bar.
Yeah, the views were great, but the appetizers were not.
We waited a long time to get the appetizers. They brought us the wrong order at first. They took that back. Wonder if they served it to someone else since it was already delivered to us? I can go into details but I don't think it will matter at this time. Good thing we got there early!
Once in the party, they served appetizers. The chicken was a little dry.
Once the buffet started, I was not to impressed with the food. The prime rib was ok, but seemed a little overcooked, as it melted in your mouth ( I do mean melted!). Now, I smoke meats at home, and I know when something is that soft that its over cooked! The Au Gratin Potatoes were not very good, and very hard to cut into the top. The salmon was ok. The chicken just ok too.
Everything just seem to be Ok, as the 3 stars show, 2.5 stars if I could give it a 1/2 star!
As a comparison, our other holiday parties at other locations were a whole lot better, and I didn't think one was that great, but heck, it was a whole lot better than this!<//Review>

None<//resp>

< review>
A girlfriend from Norway flew in so I thought I'd treat her to this fave of mine for the beautiful evening view and some good chow.  The maitre dÃ©/mgr. was the BEST!  What a neat guy.  He got us nice window seats for their killer view, and was the most on point person ever.  They are ahead of their time as they even had a special vegan dish which we ordered.  I have always ordered all manner of food there which was delicious and their vegan dish was no exception.  Liv wanted to know if the butter they served with the bread was margerine and what was in it etc.  I wanted to die as I knew it was butter and what's in that but cream?  The Mgr. Mr. Chris Gutierrez was the consumate pro and graciously offered to go and find out for her!   Mr. Gutierrez even offered to show me the new garden they got, where they now grow and get some of their FRESH ingredients from!   I love the Odyssey and always will!< /review>
